<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>
        <%= title %> | Forecasting Recessions
    </title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>

<body>
    <%- include('partials/header') %>

        <main>
            <h1>Exploratory Data Analysis</h1>

            <section>
                <h2>1. Dataset Overview</h2>
                <p>
                    The data were collected through API access from two primary sources. From Federal Reserve
                    Economic Data (FRED), we obtained the unemployment rate, inflation rate, federal funds
                    interest rate, and the oil data. From Yahoo Finance, we collected financial
                    market indicators including the S&P 500 index, the VIX volatility index, and gold prices.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The analysis primarily uses data beginning in 1968 for unemployment, inflation, interest
                    rates, and the S&P 500 index. However, VIX, gold price and oil data are only available starting
                    from 1990. As a result, analyses involving these three variables are restricted to the period
                    from 1990 onward.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>2. Data Cleaning and Preparation</h2>
                <p>
                    The recession indicator is recorded monthly and serves as the target variable for this
                    analysis. Because the original datasets were reported at different frequencies including
                    daily, monthly, and yearly, each dataset was converted to a consistent monthly frequency
                    using end-of-month values.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Two primary dataframes were constructed. The first includes unemployment, inflation,
                    interest rates, and the oil data. The second includes financial indicators
                    including the S&P 500, VIX, and gold prices beginning in 1990. Rows with missing values
                    were removed to ensure aligned observations.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The final cleaned dataset extends through 2024, and no duplicate or inconsistent records
                    were identified.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>3. Summary Statistics and Normalization</h2>

                <p>
                    The dataset contains variables measured on very different scales. For example, the S&P 500
                    is measured in large index values, while unemployment and inflation are measured in
                    small percentages. If we were to plot them together as-is, the largest numbers would
                    dominate the graph and the smaller ones would look almost flat.

                    To solve this, all indicators were put onto the same scale using a technique called
                    <b>Z-score normalization</b> (explained in more detail in
                    <a href="#zscore-explanation">Section 4</a>). In short, Z-score converts each value
                    into how far above or below its own historical average it is, so every indicator
                    can be compared on equal footing.
                </p>

                <p>
                    A correlation heatmap was also created to examine the relationships between all economic and
                    financial indicators.
                </p>

                <figure>
                    <img src="/images/correlation-of-financial-economic-indicator.png" alt="Correlation heatmap">
                    <figcaption>Figure 1. Correlation heatmap of economic and financial indicators.</figcaption>
                </figure>

                <p>
                    Based on the heatmap, we observe that <b>inflation and interest rates have a strong positive
                        correlation (0.69).</b>
                    This is because central banks raise interest rates to control rising inflation. When inflation
                    increases,
                    the Federal Reserve typically increases rates to reduce spending and slow price growth. The <b>S&P
                        500 has a negative
                        correlation with interest rates (-0.46).</b> Higher interest rates increase borrowing costs for
                    companies and reduce
                    future earnings expectations, which can lower stock prices. The <b>S&P 500 also has a negative
                        correlation with unemployment
                        (-0.37)</b> and <b>positive correlation with gold (0.41).</b>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Overall, while the correlations are moderate rather than strong, they reflect logical economic
                    relationships between monetary policy,
                    economic conditions, and financial markets.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>4. Visualization Analysis</h2>

                <h3 id="zscore-explanation">Why Z-Score Normalization?</h3>
                <p>
                    Before looking at the graphs, it helps to understand <b>why</b> the data was transformed.
                    Each economic indicator is measured in a completely different unit and range:
                    the S&P 500 is in the thousands, the interest rate is a small percentage,
                    oil is priced in dollars per barrel, and the VIX typically falls between
                    about 10 and 40. If we plotted all of these raw numbers on one graph,
                    the indicator with the largest numbers would stretch the chart and the
                    others would appear nearly flat — making it impossible to spot meaningful
                    patterns.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Z-score</b> fixes this by converting every data point into how far it is
                    from that indicator's own usual average, measured in units of that indicator's
                    typical spread. In plain terms, instead of showing a raw number, the Z-score
                    tells you: <em>"Is this value higher or lower than normal for this particular
                        indicator, and by how much?"</em> A Z-score of 0 means the value is right
                    at the average; a positive Z-score means it is above average; a negative
                    Z-score means it is below average. This puts every indicator on the same
                    scale, so we can overlay them on one graph and compare their movements
                    side by side — regardless of whether the original numbers were in the thousands
                    or in single digits.
                </p>

                <p>
                    With all indicators on the same footing, two normalized line graphs were created
                    to examine how they behave around recession periods. The first graph includes
                    unemployment, inflation, interest rates, and oil prices, while the second
                    includes the S&P 500, VIX, and gold prices.
                </p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/economic-indicators-time-series-plot.png" alt="Economic indicators graph">
                        <figcaption>Figure 2. Normalized trends of unemployment, inflation, and interest rates.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>

                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/financial-indicators-time-series-plot.png" alt="Financial indicators graph">
                        <figcaption>Figure 3. Normalized trends of S&P 500, VIX, and gold prices.</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <p>
                    The long-term line graphs show that during the first four recessions (1970s–early 1980s),
                    <b>inflation and interest rates increased before recession.</b> In contrast, during the later
                    recessions (2001, 2008, 2020), both generally declined before recession, indicating that patterns
                    vary across economic periods. Unemployment typically remains stable before recession and rises
                    afterward,
                    suggesting it behaves as a lagging indicator. Since line graphs do not measure the size of changes,
                    heatmaps
                    were created to show percentage changes 3, 6, 12, and 24 months before each recession.

                </p>


                <h3 id="avg-trajectory">4.1. Average Indicator Trajectory Before Recession</h3>
                <ul>
                    In average across all 8 US economic recessions,
                    <li><b>S&P 500 shows a small decline before recessions</b>, dropping from about <b>-0.25 to -0.35
                            (around 0.1 decrease)</b>in the last few months before economic recession, which suggests
                        the stock market starts weakening slightly.</li>
                    <li><b>VIX rises very sharply 3 months before entering into recession</b>, jumping from around -0.5
                        to almost 2.0 (about +2.5 increase), showing a sudden spike in market fear and uncertainty.</li>
                    <li><b>Interest rates and inflation both increase gradually during 2 years period before
                            recessions</b>, with interest rates rising from about <b> 0.2 to above 1.0 (around +0.8
                            increase)</b> and inflation going from about <b> 0.3 to 0.7 (around +0.4 increase)</b>,
                        meaning both are higher than usual leading into a recession</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="images/EDA/average%20line%20graph%20economic%20indicator.png"
                            alt="Average line graph economic indicator">
                        <figcaption>Figure 4. Average line graph economic indicator.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>

                    <figure>
                        <img src="images/EDA/average%20line%20graph%20financial%20indicator.png"
                            alt="Average line graph financial indicator">
                        <figcaption>Figure 5. Average line graph financial indicator.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <h3>4.2. Individual Indicator Changes Before Recession</h3>

                <p>
                    In this section, the data is normalized to percentage changes to compare the magnitude of changes
                    across different indicators and time periods. The data is then seperated into two categories:
                    1. 1970-1980: Unemployment, Inflation, Interest Rates, and S&P500
                    2. 1990-2024: S&P 500, VIX, Gold, and Oil Prices
                    That is because the data for VIX and Gold Prices are only available from 1990 onwards.
                </p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/EDA/indicators%20changes%20heatmap%201970.png" alt="Indicator heatmap 1968">
                        <figcaption>Figure 6. Indicator percentage changes before recessions (1968–2024).</figcaption>
                    </figure>

                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/EDA/indicator%20changes%20bubble%201970.png" alt="Indicator bubble plot 1968">
                        <figcaption>Figure 7. Indicator changes before recessions (1968–2024) - Bubble plot.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <p>
                    The heatmaps and bubble plots covering 1968 to 2024 suggests the following:
                </p>

                <ul>
                    <li><b>Unemployment</b>: Typically rises after recession begins, not before. This supports the idea
                        that it is not a strong early warning indicator.</li>
                    <li><b>Inflation</b>: Shows a mixed pattern, with no consistent direction before recessions.</li>
                    <li><b>Interest Rate</b>: Behavior varies across periods because it reflects policy responses rather
                        than direct economic stress.</li>
                    <li><b>S&P 500</b>: Often declines 3 to 6 months before recession. However, 12- and 24-month
                        patterns are less consistent.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>
                    These results suggest that recession patterns depend on the underlying cause of the downturn.
                </p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/EDA/indicator%20changes%20heatmap%201990.png" alt="Indicator heatmap 1990">
                        <figcaption>Figure 8. Indicator percentage changes before recessions (1990–2024).</figcaption>
                    </figure>

                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/EDA/indicator%20change%20bubble%201990.png" alt="Indicator bubble plot 1990">
                        <figcaption>Figure 9. Indicator changes before recessions (1990–2024) - Bubble plot.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <p>
                    The heatmaps and bubble plots covering 1990 to 2024 suggests the following:
                </p>

                <ul>
                    <li><b>S&P 500</b>: Gradually decreases before most recessions.</li>
                    <li><b>VIX</b>: Spikes sharply as recession approaches, especially in the short term.</li>
                    <li><b>Gold and Oil prices</b>: Does not show a consistent pattern across recessions.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>
                    These findings indicate that market-based indicators may provide earlier signals than macroeconomic
                    variables.
                </p>

            </section>

        </main>

        <%- include('partials/footer') %>
</body>

</html>